  ],
  "text": "The session key rotation is initiated by SessionBase.cycle_key() (django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py:428-437), which preserves the current session data while creating a new session key. The method calls self.create() to establish the new session.\n\nThe create() method in SessionStore (django/contrib/sessions/backends/db.py:68-79) generates a new session key via _get_new_session_key() and attempts to persist it by calling save(must_create=True). The _get_new_session_key() method (django/contrib/sessions/backends/base.py:194-199) checks if a generated session key exists using self.exists(), but this check is vulnerable to a TOCTOU race condition.\n\nConcurrency safety is enforced at the database layer: the session_key field in the Session model (django/contrib/sessions/base_session.py:28) is defined as a primary_key, ensuring database-level uniqueness constraints. When save() (django/contrib/sessions/backends/db.py:114-137) attempts to insert a session with force_insert=True, any duplicate key raises an IntegrityError. The save() method catches this IntegrityError at line 130 and raises CreateError if must_create=True (line 132). The create() method catches CreateError in its retry loop (lines 75-77) and generates a new key.\n\nCollision handling: YES. Duplicate session keys are detected and handled through database integrity constraints. When an IntegrityError occurs due to a duplicate key, CreateError is raised and caught by the create() retry loop, which then attempts to generate and persist a new session key. This mechanism ensures that cycle_key() will always produce a unique session key, preventing silent overwrites of existing sessions."
}

